{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59d588d9-f808-40da-8381-5dfaef421af9","content":"The .NET Android/MAUI build system **does not reliably use `JAVA_HOME`**. It has its own JDK discovery logic and looks for the Microsoft OpenJDK installed by the workload, not Adoptium Temurin.\n\n**Easiest fix** — install the JDK that the workload expects:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui   # includes Microsoft OpenJDK 17\n```\n\n**Alternative** — point MSBuild at your Temurin JDK explicitly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"$JAVA_HOME\"\n```\n\nOr permanently in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(JAVA_HOME)</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThe first option (workload install) is the recommended path — it ensures the JDK version stays in sync with what the SDK expects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eebbd8ed-d519-47d3-a30f-a67640cb1eb9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about what the common issue is here:\n\n.NET MAUI Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI/Android uses JDK 17. But the key issue is often about the **path** on macOS specifically.\n\nOn macOS, the Adoptium Temurin JDK installs to a path like:\n`/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`\n\n\nThe problem is usually that MSBuild doesn't automatically pick up JAVA_HOME from the environment—it looks for the JDK in specific locations or needs the `JavaSdkDirectory` property explicitly set. There's also the possibility of a JDK version mismatch if they're using .NET 6 or 7, which require JDK 11 instead of 17. The real issue is probably that .NET MAUI expects the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution, which gets installed automatically with `dotnet workload install android`, but if they're using Temurin instead, MSBuild won't find it without explicitly setting the `<JavaSdkDirectory>` property in their project file or via command line. Let me think about what specific error message they might be encountering. The real issue is likely that .NET's Android toolchain doesn't automatically pick up the Temurin JDK from JAVA_HOME on macOS—it needs either the `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property explicitly set or the Microsoft OpenJDK installed via the maui workload, since .NET 8/9 requires JDK 17 and has its own path resolution mechanism. Setting the JavaSdkDirectory property in the project file... The core issue is that .NET MAUI's Android build system doesn't actually respect `JAVA_HOME` on macOS—it needs either the Microsoft OpenJDK from the workload installation, or you can explicitly point it to your Temurin JDK by setting the `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property in your build command or project file.","outputTokens":2149,"requestId":"B808:1EC425:14D21D:1AF5F7:69FFD82A"},"id":"6c21f7e8-02c8-4a6a-9ee4-9a31b385f0f7","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:58:59.613Z","parentId":"6fcf6035-3fa0-499e-861d-97fc57158a7f"}
